    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>No Offense</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard H Berg letter replies to June 3 letter from an architect objecting to the phrase 'architect of the crime'</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 3 letter from an architect  bemoans the backhand blow dealt his profession by your use of the phrase ''architect of the crime.'' One must be led to assume that the use of phrases like ''doctoring the results,'' ''cooking the books'' or even ''policing the yard'' will bring on a host of a hues and cries.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A June 3 letter from an architect  bemoans the backhand blow dealt his profession by your use of the phrase ''architect of the crime.'' One must be led to assume that the use of phrases like ''doctoring the results,'' ''cooking the books'' or even ''policing the yard'' will bring on a host of a hues and cries.</p>
        <p>Today, almost all insult is in the mind of the recipient, and people seem almost eager to be insulted. Can we now look forward to a politically correct era of bland simple-mindedness?</p>
        <p>RICHARD H. BERG  White Plains, June 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
